---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TopBar from '../components/TopBar.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import PageHero from '../components/PageHero.astro';
import CtaBanner from '../components/CtaBanner.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const categories = [
  {
    id: 'benefits',
    label: 'Benefits',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'Is there any research on the effectiveness of the RoofBlue RETAIN™ system?',
        a: 'Yes. World-renowned researcher Dr. Brad Rowe published a 2022 study comparing stormwater retention effectiveness of various vegetative roof and blue roof systems. Dr. Anna Droz conducted additional research testing RoofBlue RETAIN\'s effects on plant growth and irrigation needs, showing significant water savings and increased plant growth in RETAIN modules.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the biggest financial advantage of a vegetative roof?',
        a: 'The primary financial benefit is extension of the lifetime of the roof — typical estimates are that a vegetative roof potentially extends the lifetime of a roof between 200 and 300 percent, by protecting the rooftop from ultraviolet radiation, large temperature fluctuations, drying winds, and punctures. Additionally, reduced membrane maintenance brings significant cost savings over time. Stormwater incentives may provide substantial monetary benefits in some communities.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What incentives are available for vegetative roofs?',
        a: 'Many municipalities offer financial incentives for vegetative roofs to reduce stormwater runoff and encourage energy conservation. Portland, Oregon provides financial, technical, and educational incentives. Washington, Illinois, New York, Montreal, California, and Maryland have implemented incentive structures. Benefits include tax credits, avoidance of impervious surface fees, grant funding, and favorable zoning. Check with your state and local governments for programs in your area.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How do vegetative roofs save energy?',
        a: 'Vegetative Roofs have been proven to bring about significant energy savings, particularly during the summer cooling season in which single story buildings can experience a reduction of greater than 25% energy use for air conditioning. Vegetative Roof soils insulate roofs from heat while plants transform heat and soil moisture into humidity for evaporative cooling. Each gallon of water transpired by the plants or evaporated from the soil surface liberates 8,000 BTU of thermal energy.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How does the LiveRoof system reduce stormwater runoff?',
        a: 'In urban areas, impermeable surfaces — streets, sidewalks, rooftops — prevent rainwater from following a natural cycle of absorption. LiveRoof vegetative roof surfaces absorb substantial rainfall, reduce runoff, lessen combined sewer overflow risks, and filter water percolating through soil. Even excess rainfall is filtered and delayed until after peak flows, allowing sewer systems more time to handle runoff.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What stormwater management benefits does the LiveRoof system provide?',
        a: 'LiveRoof vegetative roofs absorb significant rainfall, lessen flooding risk, and filter water as it percolates through soil. Plants take up heavy metals and nutrients. Even when rainfall exceeds absorption capacity, excess water is filtered and delayed after peak flows, giving municipal systems additional time to manage stormwater and reducing combined sewage overflow likelihood. Blue roof systems with RoofBlue risers provide additional detention capacity.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How do vegetative roofs reduce noise?',
        a: 'Plants, soil, and trapped air and moisture in the soil are great acoustic insulators. Studies have shown that vegetative roofs can reduce indoor sound by as much as 40 decibels, providing significant benefits for those near overhead highways and airports.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the urban heat island effect?',
        a: 'Simply put, it is the temperature difference that exists between urban areas and their surroundings. Urban areas tend to be from 7 to 10 degrees hotter due to the concentration of heat-absorbing buildings, pavement, auto-exhaust, and hot air from cooling systems. The hot air bubble results largely from a lack of vegetation and contributes significantly to smog, ozone, and dust.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How does the LiveRoof system help mitigate the urban heat island effect?',
        a: 'Traditional rooftops covered with tar, black membrane, shingles, or stone absorb sunlight. On sunny days with an air temperature of 95°F, city roofs can easily reach 175°F or more. LiveRoof acts like a protective umbrella above the roof, shading and insulating the building. Plants release oxygen and evaporate water — collectively known as evapotranspiration — acting like evaporative cooling systems to make the surrounding air considerably cooler.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'design',
    label: 'Design',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'What waterproofing systems can LiveRoof work with?',
        a: 'LiveRoof systems are compatible with nearly all waterproofing types: EPDM, TPO, PVC, bituminous, polyurethane, rubberized asphalt, inverted or conventional. We work with all appropriate waterproofing products from all manufacturers. In every case, the manufacturer\'s approved LiveRoof-compatible build-up should be specified and followed.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can you custom cut RoofStone?',
        a: 'Yes, pavers may need cutting at perimeters or around penetrations and equipment. For the cleanest cuts, LiveRoof recommends a wet saw with a 14" diamond concrete blade. Place a piece of tape over the cut line to prevent chipping. Most chop saws or circular saws require cuts on both sides of the paver. Curved cuts are made by making several angled straight cuts, and notches can be cut using an angle grinder with appropriate plastic-cutting blades.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Why does LiveRoof recommend overhead spray irrigation?',
        a: 'Spray rotor systems are the least expensive to install, easiest to maintain, and apply water most efficiently. Vegetative Roof soils are predominantly composed of inorganic aggregates with poor capillary qualities — drip irrigation requires prohibitively close tube spacing, and sub-irrigation risks root rotting and uses more water. A well-designed overhead spray irrigation system provides even coverage to the surface of plants and soil at a very low installation cost.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the difference between rooftop detention and rooftop retention?',
        a: 'Retention means a specific volume of water is held on the roof indefinitely. Detention means temporarily delaying stormwater before discharging it as runoff. RoofBlue DETAIN delays and controls stormwater flow to prevent system overflows. RoofBlue RETAIN captures and holds stormwater, transferring water upward toward plant roots as soil dries — maintaining moisture for plant health and reducing irrigation needs.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is a blue roof?',
        a: 'A blue roof is designed to slow or store stormwater runoff, easing the burden on stormwater systems. When combined with the LiveRoof vegetative roof system — which is itself an effective stormwater tool — the RoofBlue system maximizes rooftop stormwater management capability. This may greatly reduce or eliminate the need for cisterns, detention ponds, or underground storage tanks.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is a control flow drain? And how do I select the right one for my blue roof application?',
        a: 'Control flow drains are designed to slow the rate of runoff from roofs during storm events. They typically have an insert with a weir that regulates water flow and are available in a variety of heights. Flat roofs typically use lower weir heights than sloped roofs, and some models have adjustable weirs or copper flanges to inhibit root growth. A licensed professional engineer should carefully design all control flow drain systems. Common manufacturers include Raintrol by JR Smith, Zurn, Flo-Set by Josam, Thaler Metal, Accuflow by Mifab, Flash-Tite by Lexcor, and WADE.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What type of waterproofing system should be used on blue roofs?',
        a: 'Most membrane manufacturers have special requirements for blue roof applications. In the early stages of blue roof design, it is critical for engineers and specifiers to work with membrane manufacturers to select appropriate materials, thicknesses, and assembly instructions according to local code. Also confirm specifications comply with your municipality\'s requirements, as some jurisdictions have specific blue roof regulations.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How much additional weight load does a blue roof add?',
        a: 'RoofBlue DETAIN applications should hold no more than 3.5 inches of water beneath the vegetative roof system. Each inch of water weighs approximately 5.2 lbs/sq ft, so at maximum detention the blue roof solution adds up to 18.2 lbs/sq ft to the weight of the vegetative roof modules. Maximum saturated weights for RoofBlue RETAIN by module type: Lite ≤29.5 lbs/ft², Standard ≤41.5 lbs/ft², Deep ≤62.5 lbs/ft², Maxx ≤77.5 lbs/ft².',
      },
      {
        q: 'Does LiveRoof need irrigation?',
        a: 'The need for supplemental irrigation depends on plants selected, local climate, weather patterns, roof slope, and system type. In the north temperate zone, irrigation may seldom be required, but a backup system is recommended for prolonged hot, dry, windy, sunny weather. Irrigating even once per month during protracted dry weather can keep your vegetative roof looking its best. In predictably hot and dry regions, always incorporate irrigation into the design.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can RoofStone Pavers be used on ADA compliant walkways?',
        a: 'RoofStone follows roof contours and can create walkways, patios, and landing areas. It can also be used on roofs that must be ADA-compliant with slopes up to 1:48 (2.08%, or ¼ inch per 1 foot), which is the standard minimum roof slope for drainage.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is the maximum amount of time that rainwater may stand on the rooftop?',
        a: 'In our experience, most roofing assemblies recommend that water does not stand for longer than 24 hours. However, architects and engineers should confirm the maximum detention time allowable with the membrane manufacturer before specifying drain types, sizes, and placement.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How much does the LiveRoof system weigh?',
        a: 'The LiveRoof system weighs approximately 27–29 lbs/sq ft (with a media depth of 4") when fully vegetated and saturated. The soil follows FLL standards with enhanced sustainable organic content, intentionally avoiding excessive organics that shrink from decomposition or perlite that breaks down during freeze-thaw cycles.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I retrofit my existing building with a vegetative roof?',
        a: 'Retrofitting depends on structural weight-bearing capacity. A qualified structural engineer must always be consulted before installation. The LiveRoof Lite system was developed for existing buildings, featuring 2.5" of soil with saturated weight of 15–17 lbs/sq ft, expanding vegetative roof opportunities on older structures.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Where can the LiveRoof system be used?',
        a: 'LiveRoof is most commonly used on well-drained, low and mid-slope roofs atop industrial, commercial, institutional, governmental, and residential buildings that can support vegetative roof weight. Vegetative Roofs must only be installed on appropriately engineered buildings.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can the LiveRoof system be used in non-roof areas?',
        a: 'Yes, LiveRoof modules can instantly landscape median strips, patios, plazas, and malls with fully mature ground covers.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof be used in elevated planters?',
        a: 'Yes, typically on rooftop patios where load limits prevent substantial soil volumes. Fill planters with closed-cell foam except the top 4.5–6.5 inches, then set LiveRoof modules on top for visual soil depth appearance.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How can I share my vegetative roof project with others?',
        a: 'LiveRoof\'s project showcase features volunteered projects from across North America. Submit high resolution photos to sales@liveroof.com or call 800-875-1392, and your project may be featured in the next design guide printing.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'installation',
    label: 'Installation',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'How do I go about having a LiveRoof system installed?',
        a: 'Contact your LiveRoof local grower or call LiveRoof at 1-800-875-1392 or email sales@LiveRoof.com. For Ontario and Atlantic Canada, contact Kees Govers at (519) 671-5777 or kees@liveroofontario.ca.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How can a contractor become a LiveRoof Certified Installer?',
        a: 'Landscape and roofing contractors interested in offering LiveRoof installation services should contact their local representative. LiveRoof has developed an online training program for contractors on their first project covering product, installation, and maintenance specifications. Before the first project installation, LiveRoof representatives conduct in-person training with the job site foreman and installation team.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof modules be cut to fit odd dimensions and angles?',
        a: 'Yes, LiveRoof modules can be cut to size and shape using a masonry saw or reciprocating saw. When custom cutting LiveRoof modules, the cut side should abut the non-cut side of another module, in order to contain the soil and minimize the work of installation. The cut side should not abut edging on the low, draining side of the roof.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'maintenance',
    label: 'Maintenance',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'Why are frequent, brief maintenance activities critical to success?',
        a: 'The life cycle of most weeds is about four weeks. Therefore, by weeding every 2 weeks, for just a few minutes, the few weeds that come from birds and the wind are not allowed to reproduce. Lean, preventative maintenance is far more effective and economical than reactive maintenance.',
      },
      {
        q: 'How long should I set my automatic irrigation timer?',
        a: 'Measure your system\'s output using rain gauges or tuna cans placed in a line from the sprinkler. Run sprinklers for 15 minutes, measure water depth, then calculate the duration needed for your target depth (typically one inch). Adjust based on your vegetative roof\'s specific needs.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Is it okay to walk on vegetative roof plantings?',
        a: 'Minimal, sparse walking is acceptable — one person a couple times weekly. Avoid creating single paths, standing in one place, or trampling plants. Wait until foliage is dry before servicing equipment, and cover plants with plywood or foam for up to four hours. Avoid foot traffic when plants are wet or frozen.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Will I need to fertilize my vegetative roof?',
        a: 'Yes, but likely not annually. Send soil samples to a lab qualified for vegetative roof soils each spring before growth begins. If nitrogen levels are low, apply controlled-release fertilizer. Application rates typically range from 1.5 to 3.0 pounds of actual nitrogen per 1,000 square feet.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I use de-icing chemicals on my LiveRoof plants during the winter?',
        a: 'No, LiveRoof plants are damaged by de-icing chemicals. Use sand or cat litter instead for anti-slip measures after shoveling.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can LiveRoof modules be lifted to access the roof membrane?',
        a: 'Yes. Use a flat-bladed shovel to locate container edges, peel away plant material, then use pliers to lift modules. Replace modules when finished. Never use sharp instruments around roof membranes.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I use my vegetative roof as a dog run?',
        a: 'Dog urine and excrement kill succulent plants. Vegetative Roofs specifically developed for dog traffic use turf grass or lily-turf species like Liriope, requiring minimum six inches of soil. Pick up excrement and water regularly to flush urine from soil.',
      },
    ],
  },
  {
    id: 'plants-soil',
    label: 'Plants & Soil',
    faqs: [
      {
        q: 'What are the best plants to use on vegetative roofs?',
        a: 'In the Lite and Standard systems, we recommend plants with extreme drought resistance — succulent, water-holding plants like Sedums, Alliums, Sempervivums, and Delospermas. The best LiveRoof plants employ Crassulacean Acid Metabolism (CAM), making them up to ten times more efficient with water conservation than non-CAM plants. In the Deep and Maxx systems with irrigation, a broader plant palette is possible. Consult your local LiveRoof representative for climate-specific recommendations.',
      },
      {
        q: 'Can I grow vegetables or fruits in a rooftop garden?',
        a: 'Yes. Numerous vegetables, herbs, and select fruits (such as strawberries and melons) may be grown on intensive vegetative roofs that receive frequent watering, have ample sunlight, and have proper soil. Edible plants require sufficient nutrients to support their rapid growth cycle. A blend of organic soil and traditional vegetative roof growing media yields the best results, but the soil will need annual amendments to maintain volume and provide sufficient nutrition.',
      },
      {
        q: 'What is so special about LiveRoof soil?',
        a: 'LiveRoof Engineered Vegetative Roof Soil is composed of approximately 94% high quality inorganic aggregates by dry weight. It includes clay particles for nutrient binding and acid rain buffering, plus disease-suppressive organic material. The soil conforms to German FLL granulometric standards, filters rainwater, effectively grows LiveRoof plants, and is designed to last for many decades. Soil specifications vary somewhat by region depending on climate, water quality, and available components.',
      },
    ],
  },
];
---

<Layout title="FAQ – LiveRoof Vegetative Roof Systems">
  <TopBar />
  <Header />

  <PageHero
    eyebrow="FAQ"
    title="Frequently Asked"
    highlight="Questions"
    subtitle="Find answers to the most common questions about LiveRoof vegetative roof systems, design, installation, maintenance, and more."
    breadcrumbs={[
      { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
      { label: 'FAQ' },
    ]}
  />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-24 bg-white">
    <div class="container">
      <!-- Tab Navigation -->
      <div class="faq-tabs flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-12 border-b border-border pb-4" role="tablist">
        {categories.map((cat, i) => (
          <button
            class={`faq-tab px-5 py-2.5 rounded-lg text-[0.85rem] font-semibold tracking-wide transition-all cursor-pointer ${i === 0 ? 'bg-green text-white' : 'bg-mid text-text-muted hover:bg-border'}`}
            data-tab={cat.id}
            role="tab"
            aria-selected={i === 0 ? 'true' : 'false'}
          >
            {cat.label}
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- Tab Panels -->
      {categories.map((cat, i) => (
        <div
          class={`faq-panel ${i === 0 ? '' : 'hidden'}`}
          data-panel={cat.id}
          role="tabpanel"
        >
          <div class="grid gap-6">
            {cat.faqs.map((faq) => (
              <details class="group bg-mid rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-4 sm:px-7 py-5 text-dark font-semibold text-[1rem] leading-snug select-none list-none [&::-webkit-details-marker]:hidden">
                  <span class="pr-4">{faq.q}</span>
                  <svg class="flex-shrink-0 w-5 h-5 text-text-muted transition-transform group-open:rotate-45" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                    <path d="M12 5v14M5 12h14" />
                  </svg>
                </summary>
                <div class="px-4 sm:px-7 pb-6 pt-0">
                  <p class="text-text-muted leading-relaxed">{faq.a}</p>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Contact CTA -->
  <section class="py-10 md:py-16 bg-mid">
    <div class="container text-center">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-[2rem] text-dark mb-4">Still Have Questions?</h2>
      <p class="text-text-muted max-w-[480px] mx-auto mb-8 leading-relaxed">
        Our team is here to help. Reach out to your local LiveRoof Ontario representative or contact global headquarters.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-4">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-primary">Contact Us</a>
        <a href="tel:5196715777" class="btn btn-outline-dark">Call (519) 671-5777</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CtaBanner />
  <Footer />
</Layout>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const tabs = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-tab');
    const panels = document.querySelectorAll('.faq-panel');

    tabs.forEach((tab) => {
      tab.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const target = tab.getAttribute('data-tab');

        tabs.forEach((t) => {
          t.classList.remove('bg-green', 'text-white');
          t.classList.add('bg-mid', 'text-text-muted');
          t.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'false');
        });
        tab.classList.remove('bg-mid', 'text-text-muted');
        tab.classList.add('bg-green', 'text-white');
        tab.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'true');

        panels.forEach((panel) => {
          if (panel.getAttribute('data-panel') === target) {
            panel.classList.remove('hidden');
          } else {
            panel.classList.add('hidden');
          }
        });
      });
    });
  });
</script>
